node.text:
Today we announce the 35 photographers selected for the upcoming #PhotoVogueFestival exhibition through the open call on #PhotoVogue, @Picter_com and Instagram. On Picter alone we received 24.913 images, 2.949 projects by 2.513 photographers from 98 different countries, 6 continents. 
 
Here are the selected artists: @tendercoconut_, @Alessandro.Iovino_, @BettinaPittaluga, @BryanThomasphoto, @delaliayivi, @diiegotv, @di_mathopa, @ElenaHelfrecht, @Elliott.Verdier, @FabioLasin, @Gabriele.Cecconi, @heathatrottlives, @Reanie_Beanie, @l4artiste, @jaircoll, @JodiemBateman, @Juan_Brenner, @Kaiykym, @LauraPannack, @lebo.th, @LeonardPongo, @LisandroSuriel, @Kuca_Magda, @MousLamrabat, @plantationofficial, @elriveriver, @RobertAndyCoombs2, @tondopo, @SaraBennettBrooklyn, @SilvanaTrevale, @SuleikaMueller, @Sushavan_Nandy, @africatotheworldzw, @thembinkosih15, @panremembrance. The artists have been selected by an international jury consisting of experts from across the world, with different backgrounds and vision so as to try to provide the most inclusive and multifaceted perspective. 
 
Photo Vogue Festival has always tried to challenge the danger of single, monolithic stories, and to push a multiplicity of points of view. For its 6th edition, titled “Reframing History”, we wanted to explore the projects that have reclaimed an alternative, different way of telling a tale. 
For the very first time - as part of the Reframing History scouting initiative - PVF launched a grant in collaboration with Studio RM, a prestigious creative studio with offices in London and New York, specialising in colour grading and post production for film, print and digital.
The two participants that will receive a 5,000€ cash grant each, are Lisandro Suriel and River Claure. 
 
Discover more about #VIReframingHistory at the link in bio.

Insieme a @WWFItalia siamo andati alla scoperta dell'Oasi WWF Le Cesine. L'Oasi si trova all'interno di un Sito d'Importanza Comunitaria nel Comune di Vernole e il suo simbolo è la beccaccia di mare.
 
La storia di questa straordinaria Oasi, in provincia di Lecce, comincia il 13 ottobre del 1939, quando viene affittata alla sezione cacciatori di Lecce. Nel 1964 per Decreto Ministeriale viene istituita la “Riserva di caccia Cesine” e negli anni successivi le mattanze ai danni della fauna si susseguono senza sosta.
 
Ma la firma della Convenzione di Ramsar nel 1971 cambia le sorti dell’area e il 1/1/1976 Le Cesine diventano un’area di tutela e rifugio per animali selvatici. Nel 1977, a seguito della ratifica della Convenzione di Ramsar avvenuta l’anno prima, l’area diviene Zona Umida di Interesse Internazionale.
 
Il paesaggio de Le Cesine è costituito da dune, area palustre, canali di bonifica, bosco misto e macchia mediterranea. Oggi l'Oasi protegge 350 ettari ed è un ambiente umido tra i meglio conservati e più importanti dell'Italia meridionale, e si trova lungo una delle principali rotte migratorie per l’avifauna e vi sono state censite circa 180 specie di uccelli. Notevolissime sono anche le presenze di anfibi, rettili e insetti.
 
A guidarci in questo viaggio Giuseppe De Matteis, Responsabile RNS Oasi Le Cesine.
 #WWFItalia

node.text:
One of the most important names in the history of photography, @ThomasRuff_com accepted the invitation to create a cover for the September Issue of Vogue italia. In his work, Ruff uses a wide range of techniques, combining analog and digital images, computer-generated images, archival photographs, and manipulated images from newspapers, magazines, and the Internet. 
 
“Ruff’s endless devotion to redefining boundaries, meaning and grammar of the image-making practice made him an ultimate contributor for an issue that celebrates art as a form of constant rebirth.” say Emanuele Farneti (@EFarneti) and @FerdinandoVerderi, Editor-in-Chief and Creative Director of Vogue Italia.
 
Cover 9 of 9.
On newsstands tomorrow.

“I really wanted to photograph them because I think they’re the most important authors in American literature,” says @JordanMatthewWolfson, one of the most influential names in art today, who portrayed @EmmaNancyCline & Ottessa Moshfegh in @Prada on this #VogueItalia’s September Issue cover. “I relied on instinct more than thought by getting them to take a picture of themselves in a sort of embrace celebrating their strength, their femininity. Emma and Ottessa are certainly individuals, but at the same time they stand for so much more: they intuitively channel and interpret the world.” he adds.
 
“Collaboration between artists is one of the forces that this homage to Renaissance aims to bring to life. It’s Jordan’s respect, admiration and curiosity towards Emma’s and Ottessa's literary work that shaped this cover.” say Emanuele Farneti (@EFarneti) and @FerdinandoVerderi, Editor-in-Chief and Creative Director of Vogue Italia.

"Water is the symbol par excellence of regeneration, redemption, and a return to life” says @_MassimoVitali_, the artist behind this #VogueItalia’s September Issue cover. 
To celebrate new beginnings, we dedicated the issue to the idea of Renaissance, Italian for “rebirth”, working with artists to depict the idea of a sunrise. 
 
"I have never been a fashion photographer, and I confess that I initially had some perplexities when asked to shoot for Vogue Italia. Then, as the days went by, the idea of taking fashion photos in my style for the first time in my career started to resemble a challenge." says Vitali.
 
“We asked #MassimoVitali to shoot this cover at dawn in the Tuscan beach of Rosignano Solvay, where, in the mid-nineties, he took his first monumental images. We wanted to imagine how such an iconic documentation of everyday life could transform itself in a fashion context, playing with the fine line between reality and fiction that contraddisguish our industry”, say Emanuele Farneti (@EFarneti) and @FerdinandoVerderi, Editor-in-Chief and Creative Director of Vogue Italia.

Vogue Italia responded to the September’s Vogue global theme of New Beginnings with an issue dedicated to Renaissance, Italian for “rebirth”, and arguably the one word that embodies Italian art to the eyes of the world. To do so we worked with a series of contemporary artists to create original artworks that include, visually or metaphorically, the idea of a sunrise.
 
“The idea of utilizing our cover as a canvas for experimentation comes to life through a series of artworks that celebrate our September issue. This continues our research on what a cover can become: from a collaboration between an artist of today and the estate of an iconic artist of the past, to a written interview as a cover, to a painted portrait over a pre-existing fashion image, and more.” say Emanuele Farneti (@EFarneti) and @FerdinandoVerderi, Editor-in-Chief and Creative Director of Vogue Italia.
 
All clothes by @Prada.
 
A special thanks to the artists: @_MassimoVitali_, Anne Collier with the estate of @Luigi_Ghirri, @Michelangelo_Pistoletto, @Rodland.jpg, @devilintraining_, @HansUlrichObrist with Etel Adnan, @JordanMatthewWolfson with Emma Cline and Ottessa Moshfegh, @TschabalalaSelf and @ThomasRuff_com. 
 
On newsstands tomorrow.
